  "prompt": "What are those lines called that are used instead of parenthesis?",
  "response": "The lines you're referring to are called **em dashes** (\u2014). Em dashes are often used in place of parentheses to set off a phrase or clause within a sentence. They can provide a stronger break or emphasis than parentheses or commas.\n\nFor example:\n- \"She finally decided\u2014after much deliberation\u2014to accept the job offer.\"\n- \"The concert\u2014which was delayed by an hour\u2014turned out to be incredible.\"\n\nEm dashes are distinct from **en dashes** (\u2013), which are typically used to indicate ranges (e.g., \"pages 10\u201315\") or connections (e.g., \"New York\u2013London flight\").",
